    "day_number": 3,
    "title": "Articles: a, an, the",
    "explanation": "We use 'a' and 'an' before singular, countable nouns when we mention something for the first time, or when it isn't specific.\n\nUse 'a' before a consonant sound: a book, a car, a university.\nUse 'an' before a vowel sound: an apple, an hour, an idea.\n\nWe use 'the' when we talk about a specific thing, something already mentioned, or something unique (like the sun, the moon).\n\nWe usually don't use an article with plural nouns in general statements, or with most proper names.",
    "examples": [
      {
        "sentence": "I have a dog.",
        "note": "a + consonant sound"
      },
      {
        "sentence": "She is an engineer.",
        "note": "an + vowel sound"
      },
      {
        "sentence": "I saw a man. The man was tall.",
        "note": "second mention uses 'the'"
      },
      {
        "sentence": "The sun rises in the east.",
        "note": "unique thing: the sun"
      },
      {
        "sentence": "Cats are independent animals.",
        "note": "no article for general plural statement"
      }
    ],
