    "day_number": 5,
    "title": "This, That, These, Those",
    "explanation": "We use 'this' and 'that' to point to one thing (singular). We use 'these' and 'those' to point to more than one thing (plural).\n\n'This' and 'these' refer to things that are near us.\n'That' and 'those' refer to things that are far from us.\n\nWe can use these words before a noun (this book) or alone, replacing the noun (This is my book).",
    "examples": [
      {
        "sentence": "This is my phone.",
        "note": "near, singular"
      },
      {
        "sentence": "That is your house, over there.",
        "note": "far, singular"
      },
      {
        "sentence": "These are my shoes.",
        "note": "near, plural"
      },
      {
        "sentence": "Those are beautiful mountains.",
        "note": "far, plural"
      },
      {
        "sentence": "I like this book, not that one.",
        "note": "comparing near and far"
      }
    ],
